load ../std-construct-authorization.maude

--- Coverage: a standard built-in construct use is authorized with no lock (the
--- 1929 OPTION A exemption).
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-STD-CONSTRUCT-AUTHORIZATION :
  stdUse(send)
  =>* authorized(send) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Coverage: a third-party construct use authorizes when a lock authorizes it.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-STD-CONSTRUCT-AUTHORIZATION :
  thirdPartyUse(recall) locked(recall)
  =>* authorized(recall) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Bite (supply-chain lock still required): a third-party construct use with no
--- lock is never authorized. The RESIDUAL soup var means an authorization in any
--- reachable state would be a solution, so No solution proves the lock
--- requirement still bites. If [std-exempt] keyed on any use rather than only the
--- standard built-in, this would find a solution.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-STD-CONSTRUCT-AUTHORIZATION :
  thirdPartyUse(recall)
  =>* authorized(recall) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Bite (no name-only bypass): an unknown construct the compiler does not register
--- is never authorized, even with no lock. The exemption is keyed on a recognized
--- built-in registration, so a package cannot bypass the lock by claiming the std
--- namespace without a compiler built-in behind it.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-STD-CONSTRUCT-AUTHORIZATION :
  unknownUse(bogus)
  =>* authorized(bogus) RESIDUAL:Cfg .
